39:46.517 --> 40:00.298 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
GWEN IFILL: Finally, new
guidelines are out
today from the American Academy
of Pediatrics.

40:00.331 --> 40:02.934 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They recommend that, during
routine checkups,
physicians also screen children
for poverty.

40:02.967 --> 40:04.736 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Hari Sreenivasan has that.

40:04.769 --> 40:07.505 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Census figures
show one
in five children in the country
lives in poverty,

40:07.538 --> 40:12.210 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
which can contribute to higher
rates of asthma
and obesity, poor language
development, and

40:12.243 --> 40:13.911 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
increased infant mortality.

40:13.945 --> 40:19.183 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The new guidelines encourage
doctors to ask
patients about basic needs, such
as food,

40:19.217 --> 40:23.655 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
heat and housing during
well-child visits,
and to help them connect with
community resources

40:23.688 --> 40:25.490 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
that might be of help.

40:25.523 --> 40:30.161 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Dr. Renee Jenkins is a former
president of
the American Academy of
Pediatrics who currently

40:30.194 --> 40:33.398 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
teaches at Howard University
Medical School,
and joins me now.

40:33.431 --> 40:36.634 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Dr. Jenkins, what does it mean
to screen for
poverty?

40:36.668 --> 40:41.172 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. RENEE JENKINS, Former
President, American
Academy of Pediatrics: So, there
are now tools

40:41.205 --> 40:46.611 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that help us in the office when
we do well-checks
to really ask parents about food
insecurity,

40:46.644 --> 40:51.115 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
housing insecurity, whether
their young children
are in childhood educational
situations, like

40:51.149 --> 40:57.088 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Head Start or Early Head Start,
because we
recognize that if we can
intervene early on,

40:57.121 --> 40:59.724 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
very often, we can make a
difference.

40:59.757 --> 41:04.262 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Now, I know
people are very
comfortable sharing confidential
information

41:04.295 --> 41:10.201 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with their doctors, but how do
you start this
conversation, and do people open
up to you

41:10.234 --> 41:11.002 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
about it?

41:11.035 --> 41:12.837 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DR. RENEE JENKINS: Right.

41:12.870 --> 41:20.244 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Generally, we start with
something very broad,
like, do you have any problem
making ends

41:20.278 --> 41:25.416 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
meet, OK, and does this happen
often or does
it just happen sometimes?

41:25.450 --> 41:31.723 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And then that opens up a
conversation about
what some of the issues might
be. And I think

41:31.756 --> 41:37.028 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we are trying to -- what we're
recommending
is that we screen everyone. We
ask an very

41:37.061 --> 41:41.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
open-ended question like that
and then we
see where that takes us.

41:41.799 --> 41:47.739 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm sure some people are going
to be uncomfortable
to start to do that, but I think
once patients

41:47.772 --> 41:52.210 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
understand that, each time I
come, they're
going to ask me something like
that, because

41:52.243 --> 41:57.281 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it's a common problem. And as
you mentioned,
you know, one in five children
is living if

41:57.315 --> 41:59.050 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
poverty.

41:59.083 --> 42:04.789 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if it weren't for the safety
programs,
safety net programs that we
have, it would

42:04.822 --> 42:11.129 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
be even more children. So we're
just trying
to connect parents to the safety
net programs.

42:11.162 --> 42:16.701 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So, how solid
are the links
between poverty and adverse
health outcomes?

42:16.734 --> 42:18.469 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What does the research show?

42:18.503 --> 42:23.174 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DR. RENEE JENKINS: The research
shows that
there really are.

42:23.207 --> 42:30.281 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have known for quite a long
time about
the relationship, for example,
with asthma

42:30.314 --> 42:34.619 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and poor housing, OK? We have
also known about
nutrition and how, when you're
poor, you tend

42:34.652 --> 42:40.858 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to buy cheaper foods. Healthy
foods are pretty
expensive. And so in order to
make the food

42:40.892 --> 42:45.863 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
last for the entire month, you
have got to
do that.

42:45.897 --> 42:51.769 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So we have always known that.
But there is
new information now about the
stressors that

42:51.803 --> 43:01.712 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
children go through when they're
in poverty
and how these stressors do
handicap them in

43:01.746 --> 43:04.549 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
terms of their developmental
milestones.

43:04.582 --> 43:10.054 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Now, you're
also talking
about longer-term issues.

43:10.087 --> 43:18.196 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
From the report, you talk about
gene expression,
brain function, language
development and possible

43:18.229 --> 43:21.232 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
leads to psychiatric disorder.
All of that
comes from childhood poverty?

43:21.265 --> 43:25.837 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DR. RENEE JENKINS: Well, poverty
certainly
contributes to it.

43:25.870 --> 43:38.983 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But when you take the big
picture and you
look at what's happening within
the neighborhood

43:39.016 --> 43:45.189 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that these poor children may
live in and those
kind of safe -- unsafe issues,
as well as

43:45.223 --> 43:53.197 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
the stressor on parents,
parents, you know,
want to provide the best for
their children.

43:53.231 --> 43:57.301 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And when they can't, that's
stressful for
them, also.

43:57.335 --> 44:05.810 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Very often, there are not the
same sort of
ways that we relax when you are
someone who

44:05.843 --> 44:14.018 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
has resources. People who are
poor can't do
that. And so they don't have
ways to necessarily

44:14.051 --> 44:18.623 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
relieve the stresses that are
associated with
their living conditions.

44:18.656 --> 44:26.397 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So we have got stressed parents,
